init_text:
How Worried Should We Be About Screen Time During the Pandemic?

The coronavirus pandemic ended the screen time debate: Screens won. We all now find ourselves on our screens for school, for work and for connecting with family and friends during this time of social distancing and increased isolation.

But should we be worried about this excessive screen use right now? Or should we finally get over it and embrace the benefits of our digital devices?

---

In my opinion,

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Whatever happened to just relaxing with friends, having a meal or actually talking?

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: I feel like I am surrounded by robots; people who can still hear but can’t actually engage with how the person they are sitting next to

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: You feel the adrenaline from the situation; you feel human.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: You might even notice the subtlety of another person’s breathing change, the difference in their skin where they broke their collar bone once and that

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: When you have a screen between you, you can’t see any of this.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: As screen time increases, people are disengaging from their loved ones and their communities.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The more we screen, the less we actually communicate.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The less we communicate, the less common values and ideas we share, and the more alienated we become from each other.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Additionally, the less we communicate with each other, the more we are opening the door to a host of new digital communicable diseases.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The more we self-separate, the more we simmer in our own heat and stew in our own toxicity.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: I’m sure the next pandemic we face will be in some way digitally transmitted.
